elements.name: examples.Shapes

elements.documentation:
This package was meant to represent the k file Shapes.k as literally as possible given the modeling paradigm in use by Rahul - i.e. requirements should be handled by constraint elements and not SysML requirements, or constraint blocks, or in parametric diagrams.

 

When creating the class shapes, it should be noted that defining a function to be later redefined is probably not possible in SysML. Therefore the fun area : int is excluded from class Shape. (However, note that value property area : real is later given to shape - this is fine, but is still not redefined as a function).  

 

For the class Angle, it should be necessary to have a value property to capture the result of the eq function. (N.B. as will be seen in example.Shapes1 Constraint Elements not on a parametric diagram cannot be evaluated, so functions modeled as constraint blocks are used here.)  

 

Actually, it is necessary to provide connections in the parametric diagram Angle for all inputs and outputs of eq. the lack of having one parameter, like the K file (second parameter is intended to be provided by another instance of the angle class), causes the block structure to be invalid (according to Paramagic when attempting to validate the block structure for Triangle. This is important because we would generate instances of Triangle as top level instances potentially, ignoring obtuse and equilateral for the moment). The requirement in Angle is given as a constraint element but no parametric diagram exists to evaluate this constraint, and it is not possible to add constraint parameters to Angle with Angle as a "block" class (only if it is a constraint block, as fun eq is modeled). Note, in order to use eq a constraint property of type eq is added to Angle for use in the parametric diagram.

 

The same concern about whether the requirement can be evaluated holds for TAngle and Triangle.

 

One note about composition is that the SysML modeler might want to illustrate a,b,c of type TAngle by using composition with multiplicity, as shown in the OverAll Structure bdd. It is not currently known whether this structure will work with the desired constraints but it is a "pure" form of representing the desired structure for Triangle.

 

In example.Shapes1, the issue with unconnected constraint parameters is resolved by the inoperability of the requirement constraint elements remains.
